    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. Could you explain how the structural differences in the binding pockets of COX-1 and COX-2 allow for the development of more selective COX-2 inhibitors? It would be helpful to understand the specific amino acid residues involved in that selectivity.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The selectivity of COX-2 inhibitors over COX-1 arises from structural differences between the enzymes' active sites, wherein specific amino acid residues in the binding pocket of COX-2 allow for more effective accommodation and stabilization of the inhibitors. COX-2 is characteristically found in an active conformation that allows the interaction with bound COX-2-specific inhibitors (COXIBs), which exploit these intrinsic structural differences for selective affinity.\n\n\nKey to this selectivity is the Arg-Input 2 residue of COX-2, which occupies a position in the binding pocket where COX-2 inhibitors reside. In contrast, COX-1 also has an Arg but in a different position, not accommodating COXIBs but rather favoring noncovalent interactions that facilitate its natural function in heme and iron positioning. The COX-2's Arg-Input 2 differs from that of COX-1, providing COXIBs a high-affinity binding site that can irreversibly bind these inhibitors.\n\n\nAdditionally, COX-2 has two additional residues—Glu-357 and Asp-368—located close to the Arg-Input 2 that create a binding pocket with a distinct shape and properties",
      "source": "target",
